  "A rating assigned by analysts to indicate buy or sell recommendations": "",
  "A ticker symbol is a unique short alphabetic code (such as TSLA for Tesla or AMZN for Amazon) used to identify a specific publicly traded security on an exchange.": "",
  "What does 'P/E ratio' mean?": "",
  "The payout-to-expenses ratio, measuring dividend coverage": "",
  "The projected-earnings ratio, estimating future growth rates": "",
  "The price-to-earnings ratio, calculated by dividing the stock price by its earnings per share": "",
  "The profit-to-equity ratio, comparing net profit to shareholder equity": "",
  "P/E stands for Price-to-Earnings ratio. It is calculated by dividing the current stock price by the company's earnings per share (EPS), indicating how much investors pay for each dollar of earnings.": "",
  "What does 'EPS' stand for in a financial table?": "",
  "Exchange Price Spread -- the difference between buying and selling prices": "",
  "Earnings Per Share -- a company's net income divided by its number of outstanding shares": "",
  "Equity Premium Surplus -- the excess return above the risk-free rate": "",
  "Estimated Profit Share -- the projected profit distributed to shareholders": "",
  "EPS stands for Earnings Per Share. It is calculated as net income divided by the number of shares outstanding and is a key indicator of a company's profitability on a per-share basis.": "",
  "What is the 'PEG ratio'?": "",
  "The P/E ratio divided by the annual earnings growth rate, used to assess whether a stock is over- or undervalued relative to its growth": "",
  "The price-to-equity growth ratio, measuring stock price relative to equity increases": "",
  "The portfolio efficiency grade, rating how well a portfolio performs": "",
  "The profit expansion gauge, measuring how fast profits are accelerating": "",
  "The PEG ratio equals P/E divided by the earnings growth rate. A PEG below 1 may indicate the stock is undervalued relative to its growth, while above 1 may suggest it is overvalued.": "",
  "What does 'price-to-book (P/B) ratio' measure?": "",
  "The number of accounting books a company files with the SEC each year": "",
  "The stock price compared to its book value per share (total assets minus total liabilities, divided by shares outstanding)": "",
  "The stock price relative to the company's annual revenue": "",
  "The ratio of price gains to price declines over a set period": "",
  "The P/B ratio compares a stock's market price to its book value per share. A P/B below 1 may indicate the stock trades below its net asset value, while a high P/B suggests the market values the company well above its accounting value.": "",
